properties.COMMENTS: Name associated with an Aboriginal word (language and dialect not recorded) indicating waterhole (Gnallarah) or swamp place, presumably referring to a local lagoon.

A pastoral run of this name and in this locality was held by J.D. Mc Taggart in the late 1850s. It is listed as Amamoor or Police Creek. The parish was probably named for this run. [NSW Government Gazette 31 July 1857; ANPS files]. Reportedly from 1. Nga

Name derived from Amity Point, which was named by Sir Thomas Brisbane (1773-1860) in 1824, after HM Colonial Brig Amity and because of the "friendly" group of island aborigines encountered by Brisbane's party.  Refer J.D. Steele.  Brisbane Town in convic
Derived from railway station name, changed by Railways Department from Roessler to Applethorpe in 1915, in response to local anti-German sentiment.

Derived from Kabi language word "Ooramara" or "Yuramurra", indicating many spotted gum trees (Eucalyptus Maculata).  Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South East Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.112.
Reportedly named by the Queensland Smelting Company after Aldershot, Hampshire, England.

Derived from pastoral run name used by Edwin Hawkens (    -    ) (Hawkins) in 1842, pastoral overseer for Henry Suttor (    -    ), Bathurst.  Hawkins possibly obtained the name from Beau Desert, a N.S.W. run held by Henry Bayley (    -    ), a descendan
Reportedly named after town in Northern France, north-west of Cambrai, World War I battlefield.
Derived from range name, reportedly named by timbergetters, late nineteenth century, after beech trees.
Derived from pastoral run, 1841, name given by Henry Hayter Nicol (    -    ), probably because of a childhood association with Ballindean House, near Inchture, Perthshire, Scotland.

Town name derived from a sugar plantation name used in1860s, for a property on the north bank of the Albert River, owned by John Davy (    -    ) and Francis Gooding (    -    ). Beenleigh could have been a residence or farm name in Devonshire, England,

Derived from mountain and creek names, which reportedly derive from Aboriginal (Kabi language) words "bir/pir" indicating green parrot and "burrum" (from "burru") indicating mountain.  Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of Sout

Name derived from mountain, derived from Kabi language, Turrbal dialect words "birrawaman", "birwa" or "birroa", indicating, broadly, up in the sky, from "birra" sky and "wandum" climbing up.  Refer J.G. Steele.  Aboriginal pathways.  Brisbane, 1983, p.1
Reportedly named after the residence of P. Bonney (    -    ), European resident, which was a compound of beach and mere, the latter indicating marshy ground.

A mail receiving office opened in the district on February 1, 1882, was designated a post office late in 1927 and closed January 5, 1965.  From 1882, to at least 1927, the office was run by the Anderson family of Biddeston Farm from which the district pr
Reportedly derived from Kabi word "bilai" indicating sheoak tree (Casuarina glauca).

Town name derived from railway station name used by Railways Department 1887, being an Aboriginal word linked to either: 1.  Bloodwood tree (Eucalyptus Corymbosa) or 2.  "Bunuru" Brigalow tree Acacia harpadhylla, common to Yuggera and Yugumbir sub-dialec
Reportedly an Aboriginal word (language and dialect unknown), indicating Brigalow tree (Acacia Harpopylla).

Derived from Brisbane River, which was named by John Oxley (1785?-1828), Surveyor-General and explorer, in December 1823, in honour of Sir Thomas Makdougall Brisbane (1773-1860) Governor of New South Wales 1821-25, whose surname could be derived from eit

Town and railway station name derived from Blackbutt Range, named in 1863 by Surveyor Edward Millington, after Waka language Dungibara dialect word indicating Blackbutt tree (Eucalyptus Pilularis). Referred originally to what is now Township of Benarkin,
Named by Queensland Government after Sir George Ferguson Bowen (1821-1899), Governor of Queensland 1859-68.

Reportedly derived from "brook" indicating creek/watercourse, and "stede" (Dutch) or "stadt" (German) indicating place, together implying a creek-side camping place. (Milmerran Centennial, 25 September 1981).
Previously known as Dewerill (See plan B6581 and railway book Lx515)  No record of date of change.
Reportedly an Aboriginal word, language and dialect unknown, indicating crab.  Refer Nomenclature of Queensland Railway Stations.  Brisbane, 1914.
Reportedly derived from badderam, indicating red soil and red honeysuckle, Banksia sp. Kabi language, Undanbi group.  Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways.  Brisbane, 1983, p.179.

Derived from Burrum River, which is reportedly an Aboriginal word, Kabi (?) language, indicating rocks interrupting river flow. Originally called Traviston (after original freehold owner Robert Travis (    -    )) changed to Burrum Heads 1960.

Possibly derived from Aboriginal words, Bundjalung language, Yugumbir dialect, Wangerriburra clan, 1.  Coonoongra or karang-gum indicating slate coloured owl. 2.  Gunungai-garara indicating long flat or plain. Variant spellings were Canimgra (1876), Cani
Probably named after Lord Edward Bulwer-Lytton (1803-1873), politician, poet, critic and author.

Reportedly an Aboriginal word, Waka and Kabi languages, indicating ring tailed possum.  Refer F.J. Watson.  Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland.  Brisbane, 1944, p.109.

Reportedly an Aboriginal word, Yuggera language, Yugarabul dialect, indicating place of carpet snakes, from "kabul", carpet snake.  Refer F.J. Watson.  Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland.  Brisbane, 1944, p.105.

Directly from Island name, which is probably Yuggera language, Jandai dialect, Coobenpil clan term for light red "kutchi" stone "mudlo", but pronunciation has probably been subject to European misinterpretation.
Derived from Coomera River, whose name derives from Bundjalung language, Ngaraangbal dialect word indicating a species of wattle tree, the bark of which was used to stupefy fish.
Derived from Caloundra Head, which derived from Aboriginal word "cullowundoor", from Kabi language "kal/owen" indicating beech tree (Gmelina leichhardtii) and "dha" place.

Two versions of name origin are recorded: 1.  Reported by language recorders John Mathew (1849-1929), minister and     anthropologist and William Ridley (1819-1878), minister and linguist,     to derive from "kambuya" indicating egg, skull or head, from

Derived from pastoral run name, first used by Henry Stuart Russell (1818-1889) pastoralist, explorer and historian and his brother Sydenham Russell (    -    ), pastoralist in 1841, probably in honour of their mother, Cecil Charlotte Russell, nee Pembert

Originally known as Barambah, the Community's name was changed in 1932, taking the Parish name in which it was located.  Cherbourg derives from the original 1840s pastoral run name, which is probably a mistaken version of "Chirbury", the town in Shropshi
Town name derived from pastoral run name used by John Augustus Milbourne Marsh (1820-1891) pastoralist and public servant, when run was leased by him around 1844.
Town name derived from locality name used by John Flint (    -    ) selector, who named it in 18?? after a pass in Lanark, Scotland.

Derived from Mount Coolum, which comes from the Kabi word "gulum" or "kulum" indicating without or wanting, which is connected with the local legend which relates how Ninderry knocked off Coolum's head during a fight, the head becoming Mudjimba Island. R

Derived from mountain feature name, which is reportedly from a Kabi language word "guran" or "kuran" indicating tall or highest. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.106.

Derived from mountain feature name, which is reported to come from a Kabi language, Undanbi? dialect word indicating round. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.106.
Derived from Cooyar Creek, which name is probably associated with the Waka language word "kuiyum", "kuya" or "kuiyur" indicating fire.

Reportedly derived from Yuggera language, Yugarabul dialect words "kung" indicating water and "nya" to see, connected with the presence of lagoons in the area. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Bri

Derived from a pastoral run name used by James Canning Pearce (    -    )1848, but no record exists of why he used the name, however, it is reported that the name Crows Nest comes from Jimmy Crow, an Aboriginal named by early settlers, who used a hollow

Named after Edward Cotton (    -    ) orchardist and soldier, who was reportedly the first to enlist in 1915 from the district. The railway station was named in 1920 by the Railways Department at the time Soldier Settlement land was being opened for frui
Town name approved by Queensland Place Names Board 1 October 1975. Origin of town name either from corroboree site, or because of fights amongst oyster gatherers at weekend camps.
Named after William Howard (    -    ) mining entrepreneur, who was amongst the first to discover coal on the Burrum field.

Derived from railway station name, first used 2 February 1890, named after William Landsborough (1825-1886) explorer and public servant. There had been a town survey on the site in 1881, with the township being called Mellum. Refer Plan L258.1.

Named after William Henry Day (1828-1919) magistrate and farmer, who selected land in the area from 1869 and grew sugarcane on the town site.  Previously known as Terrors Creek form 18?? to 1917.  Railway opened to Dayboro from Kobble opened on 25 Sept 1

Derived from D'Aguilar Range, which was probably named by Major Edmund Lockyer (1784-1860) soldier and landowner, in September 1825, after Sir George Charles D'Aguilar (1784-1855) soldier, who served in Sicily, Spain and in India (as did Lockyer).
Derived from railway station name used from 22 January 1914, reportedly an Aboriginal word, language and dialect unknown, indicating home camp.

Ma Ma claimed to be a corruption of Aboriginal mia mia, but the latter word group is of Western Australian origin, indicating bark huts. Ma Ma was probably named by Europeans. Refer R.W.M. Dixon and others. Australian Aboriginal words in English. Melbour

Reportedly, Mapleton was a name selected by local residents in 1893, when a specific postal address was required to replace Blackall Range. Mapleton was supposed to have been taken from a contemporary novel, whose title was not recorded. (Information giv
Township name derived from railway station name first used in mid-1870s. Refer J.D. Kerr. Triumph of narrow gauge. Brisbane, 1989, p.21.

Derived from Elimbah Creek, whose name is associated with the Aboriginal word, Kabi language, Undanbi dialect, "yilam" indicating grey snake, (Demansia reticulata). Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1986, p.179.
Derived from railway station name, used by Railways Department 4 July 1907 reportedly the Aboriginal name for Canal Creek, language and dialect details not recorded.

Named after Marburg, in Saxony, Germany, probably by one or a group of German settlers in the area in 1860s. Formerly called Sally Owens Plains and Frederick (after a local settler). Marburg was officially changed to Townshend (a British general) in June
So named because of its position (between MARoochydore and COOlum).

Derived from pastoral run name first used 1842 by Evan Mackenzie (1816-1883) soldier and pastoralist and Colin Mackenzie (    -    ) pastoralist, after Kilcoy, Rosshire, Scotland. Originally called Kilcoy, the township changed name to Hopetoun 1892 (afte

Town name derived from pastoral run name first used by John Daniel Mactaggart (1823-1871) pastoralist, in 1846, after his father's farm name in Kintire, Scotland, from the Gaelic cil-church and chaomhan-beloved. Refer D. Logan. Where two rivers run. Kilk
Named after the town in Ireland.
Derived from Kabi language word "gimpi", indicating stinging tree (Laportea moroides). Originally known as Nashville.

Originally a railway station name first used from 8 June 1912, named after Alice Elizabeth Ruth Paget ( nee Haden) (    -    ) second wife of Walter Trueman Paget (1854-1930) farmer and politician, Secretary for Railways 1908-15.  Previously known as Wah

Before World War One, known as Engelsburg (after August Engels (    -    ) storekeeper), changed in 1914 to Kalbar, which is reportedly an Aboriginal word, Yuggera language?, variously interpreted as either star, or from galba or dhauwu indicating dead o

Town surveyed 7 May 1904 by Hector Munro (    -    ) surveyor, reportedly using an Aboriginal word group, Waka language?, indicating a local tree, species unknown, but possibly the popularly named "sugary" gum.
Named by Queensland Place Names Board 1 November 1963.
Formerly a railway station name, first used by Railways Department from 9 January 1913, reportedly an Aboriginal word, language and dialect not recorded, indicating box tree.

Derived from pastoral run name used by Clement Francis Lawless (1815-1877) and Paul Lawless (1817-1865) pastoralists, in 1857, using an Aboriginal word, Kabi? language, indicating scrub vine. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.220.
Formerly King King Creek, reportedly derived from an Aboriginal word, Kabi language, kauin kauin, a variant of kutchin indicating red, from the red soil area drained by Kin Kin Creek.

Town name derived from railway station name first used from 1902, reportedly an Aboriginal word, Kabi language, indicating a fight concerning a woman, from gin-woman and bombe-hit. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.241.

Named Bismarck until 1916, renamed Maclagan because of anti-German sentiment during World War I, after Brigadier Ewen George Sinclair-Maclagan (1868-1948) British regular soldier, who commanded the 3rd Brigade, 1st Division, Australian Imperial Force at

Originally a railway station name, around a settlement first called Nine Mile (Yards) and Linton (derived from Colinton). Railways Department used Linville from opening Yimbun-Benarkin rail in 1910, as Linton already existed as a place name in Victoria.
Derived from property name first used 1847? probably by Patrick Leslie (1815-1881) pastoralist, or James Hay (    -    ) pastoralist.

Derived from a corruption of Aboriginal words, Waka language, king indicating small black ants and dhurai hungry, recorded by Hector Munro (    -    ) surveyor, around 1870. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.277.

Originally known as Stinking Gully and Harrisborough, Fernvale was used first as a railway station name in 1884, when Ipswich-Lowood line was opened. The name derived from the presence of ferns in the adjacent creek.
The railway station, which is no longer in existence, was named after a town in Middlesex, England. [Nomenclature of Railway Stations, ANPS files]
Probably derived from Aboriginal koondangoor, Kabi language, indicating mountainous. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.219.

Reported to be a derivation of Yuggera language, Yugarabul dialect and/or Kabi language words "muru-kutchi-dya" indicating place of the red bills, or black swans. Refer F.J. Watson. vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland.

Probably derived from Pastoral Run name, which is listed in Grooms Almanac 1885 with nearby Cabarlah as the Post Town. The Highfields Agricultural Reserve was proclaimed in 1860.  The Highfields No.1  School opened in 1870 in what had been the Rising Sun

Reportedly an Aboriginal word, one interpretation being Waka language, unknown dialect, indicating white ant (termite) beds, given by Hector Munro (    -    ) surveyor, to Surveyor-General 6 April 1914 (In letter 1900/ 18213DB). Alternate interpretation

Derived from Mary River, named by Sir Charles Augustus Fitzroy (1796-1858) Governor of New South Wales 1846-54, in memory of his wife Lady Mary Lennox (    -1847) who was killed at Government House, Parramatta, on 7 December 1847. Note that the River was

Originally known as Jaumbill (Waka? word for yam?), named Hivesville after G. Hives (    -    ) pioneer settler, at the request of James Braidwood Edwards (    -    ) MLA Nanango 1920-47. Railways Department used name for station 2 March 1923.

Reportedly named after Colonel Henry Venn King (1841-1929) soldier and pastoralist, and his brother G.B. King (    -    ) pastoralist, of Gowrie pastoral property. Refer Toowoomba Chronicle, 22 November 1928.

Township name derived from locality name first used by John King (1853-    ) pioneer selector, Portion 194, Parish of Neumga 1882. King sank the first well in the district, hence the name Maidenwell. Refer Maidenwell-Wengenville Centenary Committee. In t

Originally a railway station name used by Railways Department from 1910, from a family name associated with the Moore family of Colinton grazing property. John Moore (    -    ) married ????? Harlin, daughter of Thomas Harlin (1832-1913) headmaster of Br

Name derived from railway station, named 1884, replacing The Scrub and Cairnhill as local names. Lowood was used by Railways Department because of the local prevalence of low Brigalow scrub. Refer R.S. Kerr. Confidence and tradition. Esk, 1988, p.101.

Name derived probably from Gooneburra language word group, meel indicating eye and merran lookout. Name originally applied to the hill feature known now as Mount Domville. Refer M. French. Conflict on the Condamine. Toowoomba, 1989, p.121.

Town name derived from the series of peaks and hills termed the Glass House Mountains, so named because three of the most prominent were sighted on 17 May 1770 by Lieutenant James Cook RN (1728-1779) navigator, HM Bark Endeavour. Refer J.C. Beaglehole. T

Reportedly derived from Aboriginal words, Bundjalung language, Yugumbir dialect, dhim indicating end and boom indicating sound, ba place, interpreted as echo. Alternatively could be jaboom eidble grub and ba place.
Reportedly derived from a Kabi language word djimna meaning place of leeches. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal Pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.218.

Originally Limestone from 1827, Ipswich was the town name approved by Sir George Gipps (1791-1847) soldier and Governor of New South Wales 1837-46. Gipps approved the plan submitted by Henry Wade (    -    ) surveyor, in 1843, showing the name Ipswich. T
Originally a village name (NSWGG 11 April 1855, p.1102), Gatton is reportedly derived from English town name of Gatton in Surrey.
Town name probably derived from Parish name, which possibly derived from Scottish place name Malleny, a village in Midlothian.
Reportedly named after John Harris (1819-1895) and George Harris (1831-1891) businessmen from Brisbane and Ipswich, who had a store and cotton ginnery in this area.

Named by Surveyor-General, New South Wales, after town survey lodged in April 1857 (Surveyor A.F. Wood (    -    )). Name possibly suggested by William Gray (    -1849) carrier and merchant of Ipswich, after a Yorkshire village near Northallerton.

Reportedly derived from Aboriginal word "dugai/tugai", language details not recorded, indicating mountain spur place. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.103.

Name derived from pastoral run name first used 1841 by Henry Dennis (    - 1847) pastoralist, reported to be an Aboriginal word, language and dialect not recorded, indicating a long way off. Town surveyed by G.T. Weale (    -     ) surveyor, June 1871. R

Town name derived from Laidleys Plain, named by Allan Cunningham (1791-1839) botanist and explorer, 22 June 1829, after James Laidley (1786-1835) Deputy Commissary General, Sydney 1827-35. Refer J.G. Steele. The explorers of the Moreton Bay District 1770

Originally a pastoral run name used by C.W. Pitts (    -    ) pastoralist in 1854, Goombungee is probably a corruption of an Aboriginal word goubunga or gonbunga, reportedly the descriptive name for the area in a language and dialect not accurately recor

Derived from pastoral run name used by Patrick Leslie (1815-1881) pastoralist in 1840-41, an Aboriginal word indicating either: 1. Fire black tribe, corruption of gooneburra. Refer M. French. Conflict on the Condamine. Toowoomba, 1989, p.121. 2. Shield (

Reportedly an Aboriginal word, Waka language, Bujiebara dialect, indicating kurrajong tree and the shield made from it, probably a variant taken from the Kabi language, gudmeri or kunmarin. (Kurrajong=sterculia diversifolia).

Named by Sir Ralph Darling (1772-1858) soldier and governor, 16 July 1827, in honour of the family title of the Earl of Stradbroke, father of Captain Henry John Rous RN (1795-1877) naval officer, commander of HMS Rainbow, which carried Governor Darling t

The name was given to a railway station on the Killarney line.  Evidently, It had been the name of the district, 'a flat where emus resort and camp'. [Nomenclature of Railway Stations] Emu Vale pastoral run was listed in Grooms Almanac of 1885 with Warwi
Reportedly Grandchester is an artificially compounded name from the Latin grandis-great and chester-camp. Known as Bigges Camp before 1865, the town was named by the Surveyor-General 30 August 1865.
Name derived from pastoral run name first used by George Gershon Mocatta (1815-1893) pastoralist and merchant in 1842.

Derived from pastoral run name used by Henry Hughes (    -    ) and Frederick N. Isaac (    -    ) pastoralists, who used Gowrie in place of their initial name of Stanbrook, from 1847. Gowrie is most probably a corrupted Aboriginal word from cowarie, whi

Renamed by Queensland Place Names Board 1 September 1980 from Greenmount West. The name Greenmount derived from a selection name used by Donald Mackintosh, farmer and MLA Cambooya 1899-1912 and MLA Pittsworth 1912-1915.
Name derived from pastoral run name first used by Richard Jones (1786-1852) merchant and pastoralist, around 1841.
Derived from Kabi language, Undanbi/Nalbo dialects, word "yulu" indicating eels. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1986, p.179.

Town name derived from Aboriginal name Ngumundi (personal name of a clan leader). Kabi language, Undanbi/Nalbo dialects. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1986, p.179.  Previously known as Eerwah around 1890. Name changed because of confl
Reportedly a Kabi language word indicating rain forest. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.190.
Derived from pastoral run name used from 1850s by William Collins (    -    ) pastoralist, after the village of Rathdowney, Ireland.

Derived from pastoral run name used from ca.1849 by Charles Robert Haly (1816-1892) pastoralist, politician and public servant, using Waka language word, Bujiebara dialect, dha-bengga indicating place of jumper ants. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathway
Originally named Oaky, spelling of Oakey was adopted 22 August 1940. Original survey was May 1869, first sale was 28 June 1870.
Derived from pastoral run name used first by John Campbell (    -1876) pastoralist and merchant, in 1841.

Originally known as "Merriman's Flat" which was the name of the Kuskopf's property. The Kuskopfs arrived in 1881 and were among the first white settlers. Later the name "Palmwoods" was chosen due to the Piccabeen palm groves that grew in abundance in the

Railway station and township (1899) originally named Pinbarren, but changed to Carura then to Pomona in 1900. Pomona was suggested by the Pinbarren Agricultural and Progress Association, because of the fruit growing potential of the area, Pomona being th

Derived from Nerang River name, reportedly from Bundjalung language, Ngaraangbal variant, words indicating either small river, or shovel nosed shark, latter from neerung or neerang. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.58.
Derived from Neurum Creek, being a Waka language, Dungidau dialect word indicating warts, sores or pock marks. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisbane, 1983, p.255.

Named after pastoral run separated from Clifton Station in the 1840s.  Lessees included Philip Pinnock, John Gammie, Joseph King and Joshua J. Whitting. [NSWGG, Thomas Hall] Sydney May suggests that the name is derived from Old English (Pill - a creek an

Named after the Rosewood tree (Acacia harpophylla) once plentiful in this area. A huge tract of land from Marburg to Lowood was named the Rosewood Scrub and was the centre of an early timber industry.

Formerly named Noosa, new name of Noosa Heads was approved by Governor in Council 17 September 1988. Name derived from Noosa Head, European imposed name using a corruption of the Kabi language word nuthuru, indicating ghost or shadow. Refer F.J. Watson.

Name of city originated with the naming in 1799 of Red Cliff Point by Lieutenant Matthew Flinders (1774-1814). Humpybong and Red Cliff were used as names in the penal period 1824-25, though John Oxley (1785?-1828) NSW Surveyor General used both Red Cliff

Name is derived from the feature name Noosa Head, which is a European imposed corruption of a Kabi language word nuthuru, indicating ghost or shadow. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 194

Town name changed from Polson to Pialba by Executive Council decision 19 March 1931. There are three possible meanings for Pialba: 1. From Kabi language, place of fighting, from bai/ya fight and ba - place. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four represe
Named after ?????? Traves (    -    ) grazier?, 1860s?, named by Surveyor- General, town surveyed 1909.
Surveyed in 1888 by W.E. Hill (    -    ), name reportedly derived from Peach Trees, from Peach Tree Crossing, because of the presence of a peach tree at the crossing of the Stanley River.

Named after either Thomas Pratten (    -    ) European settler, or his son G.L. Pratten (    -    ) surveyor. Refer Toowoomba Chronicle, 22 November 1928. The township area was reportedly named Darkey Flat, because of an Aboriginal campsite.

Named after either Thomas Pratten (    -    ) European settler, or his son G.L. Pratten (    -    ) surveyor. Refer Toowoomba Chronicle, 22 November 1928. The township area was reportedly named Darkey Flat, because of an Aboriginal campsite.

Named after either Thomas Pratten (    -    ) European settler, or his son G.L. Pratten (    -    ) surveyor. Refer Toowoomba Chronicle, 22 November 1928. The township area was reportedly named Darkey Flat, because of an Aboriginal campsite.
Name derived from Mountain feature, which was reportedly named after Thomas Alford (    -    ) manager of Coochin Coochin pastoral run in the 1870s.
Probably named because of the proximity of the northern branch of the Maroochy River.

Originally used as a railway station name, from 11 January 1918, from the name of a pastoral run taken up in 1844 by Richard Jones (    -    ) pastoralist, using a Waka language word, mondhur indicating small ant. Original railway station name was Koobli

Originally called Razorback, local residents led by Henry Smith (    -    ) storekeeper, requested Montville, an artificial name from mont = mountain and ville = town. Changed officially to Montville 30 November 1897. Possibly Edward Smith (    -    ) an

Originally a railway station name, used by Railways Department from 1886, reportedly a "manufactured" word using Yuggera language words mun = much and billa = water, indicating a large lagoon. Refer S. May. Queensland Times, 1 March 1957.

Named after C.W. Pitts (    -    ) pastoralist, Goombungee pastoral run, 1854. Town name changed from Beauaraba to Pittsworth 20 August 1915. Railway station in the town had been called Pittsworth since 1887.

Derived from an Aboriginal word of Sydney area dialect, reported in ? White. Voyage to New South Wales. London?, 1789, quoted in R. Strahan. A dictionary of Australian mammal names. Sydney, 1981, p./, as indicating brush tailed phasogale.
Reportedly named after a village in Eire. Refer Milmerran Centennial 25 September 1981.
Formerly named Bingham, River Heads was renamed by Governor in Council on 22 November 1986.

Town surveyed 1884 by J.E. Palisser (    -    ), name derived from Mooloolah River, reportedly an Aboriginal word, Kabi language, Undanbi/Nalbo language indicating place of black snakes or place of schnapper. Refer J.G. Steele. Aboriginal pathways. Brisb
Derived from pastoral run name, which was reportedly a corruption of an Aboriginal word, Waka? language, unknown dialect, indicating kurrajong tree.

Named after a village in Ireland by the early Darling Downs squatters, Patrick Leslie and Ernest Dalrymple, although they both came from Scotland.  The name means 'a bend in the creek'. [Brisbane Telegraph, ANPS files]
Town named after Michael Tansey (    -1911) selector, resident on "Lakeview" from 1877. Refer D. Logan. Where two rivers run. Kilkivan, 1988, pp.115-6.

Reportedly a corruption of Aboriginal words, Kabi language, nguruin = emu and ba = place or belonging to. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.114. Previously Aalberg. Shown on 1883

Derived from Ninderry Range, which name is a corruption of the Kabi language word nyindur / durree, indicating place of scrub leeches. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Brisbane, 1944, p.107.

Derived from sugar plantation name (1868) first used by George Raff (1815- 1889) merchant, sugar grower and politician, and also from use as station name by Railways Department, June 1888?. Raff was born at Forres, Morayshire, Scotland.
Town of Tawan shown on 1889 survey plan T4291
Derived from the name of an outstation on Rosalie Plains pastoral run. Town surveyed in 1911.

Originally named as a town by Queensland Place Names Board 1 February 1972. Emu - possibly because of the number of emus in the district. The swamp north-west of the hill is known as Emu Swamp and it is certain that the tribesmen hunted emus and swamp wa

Derived from Parish name, from pastoral run name used from 1855, reportedly an Aboriginal word combination, Waka language, from murra = water and kung = plenty. Refer F.J. Watson. Vocabularies of four representative tribes of South Eastern Queensland. Br

Township name is presumed to be derived from a property name used nearby by Alexander Jenyns Boyd (1842-1928) agricultural journalist, schoolteacher and soldier, when he established a sugar plantation in the area in 1871. Ormeau probably comes from Ormea
Reportedly an Aboriginal word, language and dialect not recorded, indicating proceed or go away.

Yarraman is most probably a English/Aboriginal "pidgin" word which indicated horse to both groups of people. Possibly it comes from yira = teeth, implying long teeth, but its overall origin is obscure. Refer R.M.W. Dixson, W.S. Ramson and M. Thomas. Aust
